[2]
From: C.LEAKE@lshtm.ac.uk (Colin Leake)
ubject: Yellow fever in Asia.
Why Yellow Fever has apparently never spread to Asia is still one of
the fascinating questions of arbovirology. A variety of ideas,
possibly acting ttogether, have been proposed including
cross-protection by other flaviviruses, apparent inferior vector
competence of Asian strains of Aedes aegypti and possible ecological
factors (see Monath chapter 51 in the Arboviruses: Epidemiology and
Ecology volume 5. CRC Press 1988. p 171- 172)
The argument that dengue protects against YF is not really valid as
dengue is present in Africa and increasingly in the Americas. If one
looks at the distribution of related flaviviruses it would seem a
better bet to suggest that Japanese encephalitis would fit this
argument better as the westward distribution of JE seems to have
become restricted to Nepal, India and Sri Lanka and the far east of
Pakistan.
One important factor tending to restrict Yellow Fever in Africa to
the rain forest maintenance cycle and working against eastward
spread was probably identified by David Gillett many years ago. He
found that in the East African emergence zones the strains of
Aedes simpsoni (now known to be Aedes bromeliae) were found to be
virtually non-man biting. Thus the link between the forest
maintenance cycle and establishment of an urban Aedes aegypti-man
cycle was broken.
The principal concern today must be that container breeding urban
Aedes aegypti and Aedes albopictus are now at dangerously high levels
in many areas. Dengue viruses transmitted by these mosquitoes are
hyperendemic in S.E. and S. Asia and transmission in the
Americas continues to intensify with severe dengue now being reported
from many areas of the Americas. The risk of YF outbreaks in
endemic areas has therefore never been greater. As the movement of
dengue-viraemic humans is a very important factor in spreading dengue
viruses a similar risk must be considered for Yellow Fever.

Colin Leake PhD
Vector Biology and Epidemiology Unit
London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine.
