From: sklam@pc.jaring.my
Date: Tue, 05 Mar 1996 06:00:38 +0800
There is stringent requirement for evidence of vaccination against YF in
persons coming into Asia from YF endemic areas and this could help explain
why the disease has not made an appearance. I don't think the presence of
dengue or any other members of the flavivirus family has anything to do with
its exclusion since there is no cross immunity in humans. The absence of
monkeys will minimise the chances of survival of the virus in certain parts
of Asia. Reduced capacity of indigenous Aedes aegypti to support YF virus
has not been proven.
The speed of travel and the increase in trade and tourism poses a real
threat and the emergence of YF in Asia is a distinct possibility. This issue
has been discussed in a number of meetings on emerging diseases and it is
recommended that YF-sensitive countries monitor the situation carefully.

S.K. Lam, PhD
Director, WHO Centre for DF/DHF
Department of Medical Microbiology
University of Malaya
50603 Kuala Lumpur
